etymologies: mid 19th century; earliest use found in Thomas Huxley (1825–1895), biologist and science educationist. From pro- + ancient Greek κοῖλος hollow + -ous

definitions: Designating or relating to vertebrae whose centra are concave anteriorly. Also: (of a reptile) having such vertebrae, as a crocodile. Compare "amphicoelous", opisthocoelous.
